The '''Private Subscription Theatre''' more commonly known as the '''Chowringhee Theatre''', was an historic theatre in [[Calcutta]] (now named Kolkata) in India, founded in 1813 and closed in 1839.
The Chowringhee Theatre was situated on [[Chowringhee]] Road. A number of short-lived theatres had been founded in the city since the [[Calcutta Theatre]], but the Chowringhee Theatre was to be first permanent professional public theatre. The theatre was built on funds by private donations on subscriptions by shares of 100 Rs each. It was able to accommodate 300 people and was thereby the most spacious theatre in Calcutta at the time. The theater was protected by the Governor-General and became one of the leading theatres in Calcutta and India. Reviews of the performances at the theatre was regularly published in the press. One of the star attractions of the theatre was the hugely popular actor [[Esther Leach]]. Chowringhee Theatre was the first English theatre more frequented also by Indians, and inspired the development of English style theatre among Indians. The theatre was destroyed by fire in May 1839 and replaced by the [[Sans Souci Theatre (Calcutta)|Sans Souci Theatre]].
