'''Edith Sharpley''' (1859–1940) was the Classical Lecturer at [[Newnham College, Cambridge]] from 1884 to 1910.{{sfn|Gloyn|2015}}{{sfn|Gloyn|2016}}

==Life==
Sharpley was the second of ten children{{sfn|Whyles|2016}} born to Sarah McNicoll and Dr Thomas Sharpley in [[Louth, Lincolnshire|Louth]] in Lincolnshire. She was born on 24 January 1859<ref name=venn/> and went to several schools in Louth, [[Taunton]] and Paris before attending [[Manchester High School for Girls|Manchester High School]]. She started at [[Newnham College]] in 1879, eleven years before her sister Mary McNicoll Sharpley in 1890.{{sfn|Whyles|2016}}

Sharpley is the first student at Newnham who is recorded as having coxed a boat on the [[River Cam]] - in 1879. This was fifteen years before bicycles were permitted at Newnham.<ref>[http://newnhamcollegeboatclub.com/History.html History], Newnham College Boat Club, Retrieved 15 February 2017</ref> She took a [[British undergraduate degree classification#First-class honours|first]] in part II of the [[Classical Tripos]] for which philosophy was her specialist subject.  She then became a lecturer in Classics at the college, focussing on teaching rather than research and writing. She was a lifelong correspondent of [[Eleanor Sidgwick]] and assisted [[Blanche Athena Clough]] in caring for her aunt [[Anne Clough]]{{sfn|Gloyn|2015}} who had been Newnham's first principal. Sharpley was the first registrar of the roll of students and became vice principal in 1911.  One student wrote of "the fastidiousness of her taste and the ruthlessness of her judgement".{{sfn|Stray|p=401}}

Sharpley was elected to Newnham's governing body from 1919 to 1922. She died on 14 April 1940.<ref name=venn>[http://venn.lib.cam.ac.uk/cgi-bin/search-2016B.pl?sur=sharpley&suro=w&fir=edith&firo=c&cit=&cito=c&c=all&z=all&tex=&sye=&eye=&col=all&maxcount=50 Sharpley search], Lib.cam.ac.uk, Retrieved 16 February 2016</ref>

