{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2012}}
''' Ernest Walker Marwick '''  (1915-1977) was a Scottish writer noted for his writings on [[Orkney]] folklore and history.

Marwick's father was a travelling salesman who had a [[smallholding]] in the parish of [[Evie, Orkney|Evie]], to the north of [[Mainland, Orkney]]. Diagnosed with [[Scoliosis]] in 1925 when he was ten-years-old, Marwick could no longer attend school as his days had to be spent lying on a wooden board. He used the time of illness to read extensively.{{sfnp|Fergusson|2006|pp=91, 92|ps=}}

After Marwick's marriage his home provided a meeting-place for local intellectuals, including [[George Mackay Brown]] and [[Robert Rendall]].{{sfnp|Fergusson|2006|p=94|ps=}} His ''Anthology of Orkney Verse'' was published in 1949.{{sfnp|Murray|Murray|2004|p=40 |ps=}}

From 1955 to 1960 he was on the staff of the ''[[Orkney Herald]]'' newspaper.  He subsequently moved to ''[[The Orcadian]]'', his writing covering literary subjects.{{sfnp|Murray|Murray|2004|pp=82, 99|ps=}} Other media work undertaken by Marwick included broadcasting on local and Scottish national radio programmes.{{r|Ljosland}}

Ernest Marwick was a founder member of the [[Orkney Heritage Society]].{{sfnp|Robertson|1991|p=xvi|ps=}}

He died in July 1977, having swerved off a straight road and crashed into a farm steading when driving.{{sfnp|Fergusson|2006|p=259|ps=}} In 2015, one hundred years after his birth, [[Orkney International Science Festival]] focused attention on the contributions he made to Orkney's heritage.{{r|Science}}

==Selected works==
*''An Anthology of Orkney Verse'' (1949)
*''The Folklore of Orkney and Shetland'' (1975)

